STA36728 | Time Series: Time Series | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36728&SEMESTER=S15 | instructors:Schervish, Mark prereq:36705 or 36707 description:The course is designed for graduate students and advanced undergraduate students.  It will introduce the analysis and some of the theory of sequences of serially-dependent random variables (known as time series).  Students should already have learned mathematical probability and statistics, including multivariate and conditional distributions, linear regression, calculus, matrix algebra, and the fundamentals of complex variables and functions.  The focus will be on popular models for time series and the analysis of data that arise in applications.
STA36729 | Observational Causal Inference | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36729&SEMESTER=F14 | instructors:Sales, Adam description:Observational Causal Inference refers to the study of cause-and-effect relationships without randomized treatment assignment. This course will explore issues of statistical estimation and inference in a variety of popular causal inference designs. These include randomized experiments?as a conceptual foundation?instrumental variables, regression discontinuity, difference-in-difference and matching. We will discuss statistical techniques such as randomization-based inference, sensitivity analysis and propensity scores. Based on time constraints and class interest, we may discuss graph-based causal search algorithms, causal mediation analysis, or spillover effects.
STA36733 | Probability Models and Stochastic Processes: Probability Models and Stochastic Processes | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36733&SEMESTER=S15 | instructors:Ventura, Valerie description:Topics will include: Discrete time Markov chains (MC), stationary and limiting distributions, reversible chains, Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), Poisson processes, birth and death processes, continuous time MC.
STA36749 | Experimental Design for Behavioral and Social Sciences | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36749&SEMESTER=F14 | instructors:Seltman, Howard description:Statistical aspects of the design and analysis of planned experiments are studied in this course. A clear statement of the experimental factors will be emphasized. The design aspect will concentrate on choice of models, sample size and order of experimentation. The analysis phase will cover data collection and computation, especially analysis of variance, and will stress the interpretation of results. In addition to weekly lecture, students will attend a computer lab once a week. Prerequisite: 36-202, 36-220, or 36-247.
STA36750 | Statistical Computing | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36750&SEMESTER=S15 | instructors:Freeman, Peter description:A detailed introduction to elements of computing relating to statistical modeling, targeted to advanced undergraduates, masters students, and doctoral students in Statistics. Topics include important data structures and algorithms; numerical methods; databases; parallelism and concurrency; and coding practices, program design, and testing. Multiple programming languages will be supported (e.g., C, R, Python, etc.). Those with no previous programming experience are welcome but will be required to learn the basics of at least one language via self-study.
STA36752 | Advanced Probability Overview | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36752&SEMESTER=S15 | instructors:Lei, Jing description:This course is a one-semester overview of topics in Probability Theory. After a brief introduction to measure and integration theory, the focus will be on issues of immediate use to statisticians, such as modes of convergence, limit theorems, laws of large numbers, martingales, and other topics as time allows.
